{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649209"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:02:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:02:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18355"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18355"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.04,0.68,0.04,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11073"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74715"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11073"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18355"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60198"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25849"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74715"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of different nerves responsible for the cutaneous innervation of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following areas does the medial plantar nerve innervate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Entire plantar surface","Lateral one and a half toes and lateral sole","Medial three and a half toes and medial sole","Dorsum of the foot","Heel and posterior sole"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe medial plantar nerve is a branch of the tibial nerve, which itself is a branch of the sciatic nerve. It plays a crucial role in providing sensory and motor innervation to specific areas of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial three and a half toes and medial sole\u003C/strong\u003E are innervated by the medial plantar nerve. This nerve provides sensory innervation to the skin of the medial three and a half toes and the corresponding part of the sole of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral one and a half toes and lateral sole\u003C/strong\u003E - This area is innervated by the lateral plantar nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeel and posterior sole\u003C/strong\u003E - This area is innervated by the medial calcaneal branches of the tibial nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorsum of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - This area is primarily innervated by the superficial peroneal nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEntire plantar surface\u003C/strong\u003E - The plantar surface is divided between the medial and lateral plantar nerves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The medial plantar nerve provides sensation to the medial three and a half toes and the corresponding part of the sole of the foot.","The medial plantar nerve is a branch of the tibial nerve, which is part of the sciatic nerve.","The medial plantar nerve also supplies motor innervation to some intrinsic muscles of the foot."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60198"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18355"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60198"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T16:02:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T16:03:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11073"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74715"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving